Harvard students take part in a course to teach them enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year prompted all of its students to sleep more, in an effort to combat the growing culture of macho studios throughout the night when students do not sleep and encourage caffeine.
The academics found that students at the world's most famous university are often clueless when it comes to the basics of caring for themselves.
The course was designed by Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School Medical School and specialist at Brigham Hospital and women's hospital, which he believes is the first of its kind in the US.
He was inspired to start the course after lecturing on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“In the end, a girl came to me and said, ‘Why are you telling me this now, in my senior year?’
She said no one ever told her about the importance of sleep - which surprised me," she said for The Telegraph.
The course, which was first introduced this year, explains to students basic information on how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance and improve their overall wellbeing.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the University's medical services, said that the university decided to establish a course after finding that students were really unsleeping within a week.
The hourly course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In one part is a picture of student dormitories, where students click on cups with coffee, curtains, sneakers and books on the effects of caffeine and light and on how athletic performance is influenced by the lack of sleep and the importance of proper sleeping habits.
In another part, participants are informed how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons then encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know that student behavior will not change immediately.
However, we believe that they have a right to know - just as you have a right to know the effects of smoking cigarettes on health," Professor Czeisler added.
The culture of pride in "studying all night" still exists, adding that modern technology and ever-growing pressure on students mean that the problem of sleep deprivation is increasing.
Enough sleep of good quality should be a "secret weapon" student to combat stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, he said - even to avoid gaining weight, because sleep deprivation switches the brain into a hunger mode, so that one is still hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student of chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design a course that one of his classes graduated last year during her first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to push on the course.
He hopes that the next step will be to ask all graduate students to complete a similar study program before entering a competitive institution.
The professor recommended students to consider setting the alarm for when to go to bed, as well as when to wake up, and to be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting that may upset your circadian rhythm, leading to falling asleep problems.
